{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_24","type":"reasoning","text":"**Deciding on highest priority task**\n\nI see that I already have 15 items, so no need to append anything. The contract says to add only if there are fewer than 15. I think the highest-priority unchecked IQ item is IQ-016, but that's an obsolete doc skeleton, which feels weird. \n\nIt might make more sense to choose IQ-047, which seems more relevant and recent. This way, I can focus on something that’s likely intended for deeper work and real code!\n**Planning implementation details**\n\nI need to maintain the queue and derive from the next unchecked WS*, but since I have at least 15 already, I can skip adding anything. My focus now is to implement IQ-047 with deep work and tests.\n\nI notice the file has a sorting helper based on relative offsets and bytes, but it lacks original indices. I could build new helpers, perhaps using heapsort with triple arrays for start, end, and index to ensure stability and lookup accuracy. I’ll define a function to compute and sort while maintaining a deterministic order using the original index as a tiebreaker.\n**Refining function requirements**\n\nI might need to include `out_nbytes` since upcoming IQ-048 requires indexed lookup helpers that return original tensor indices. This means the function should output sorted absolute start and end positions along with the original index mapping. \n\nThe current resolver sorts relative offsets and bytes in place, which causes the original indices to be lost. It seems better to implement this with temporary arrays and a custom heapsort, tying by start, then end, then index. \n\nI’m also considering avoiding memory allocation dependencies and instead asking the caller to supply scratch arrays to keep it simpler. I'll define the interface to take inputs directly from the caller, ensuring all essential information is passed as needed.\n**Implementing tensor resolution and sorting**\n\nFirst, I need to resolve the range